03995nam a22005535i 9780300133165DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001331657 a10.12987/97803001331652doi  a(DE-B1597)484837  a(OCoLC)1013938231  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aMUS0280002bisacsh04a780.9471 aGasparov, Boris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFive Operas and a Symphony :bWord and Music in Russian Culture /cBoris Gasparov. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b88 musical illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Literature and Thought Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: In the Shadow of Literature -- t1. Sound and Discourse: On Russian National Musical Style -- t2. Farewell to the Enchanted Garden: Pushkin, Glinka's Ruslan and Ludmila, and Nicholas's Russia -- t3. Eugene Onegin in the Age of Realism -- t4. Khovanshchina: A Musical Drama, Russian-Style (Wagner and Musorgsky) -- t5. Lost in a Symbolist City: Multiple Chronotopes in Chaikovsky's The Queen of Spades -- t6. A Testimony: Shostakovich's Fourth Symphony and the End of Romantic Narrative -- t7. ''Popolo di Pekino'': Musorgsky's Muscovy in Early Twentieth-Century Europe -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this eagerly anticipated book, Boris Gasparov gazes through the lens of music to find an unusual perspective on Russian cultural and literary history. He discusses six major works of Russian music from the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, showing the interplay of musical texts with their literary and historical sources within the ideological and cultural contexts of their times. Each musical work becomes a tableau representing a moment in Russian history, and together the works form a coherent story of ideological and aesthetic trends as they evolved in Russia from the time of Pushkin to the rise of totalitarianism in the 1930s.Gasparov discusses Glinka's Ruslan and Ludmilla (1842), Mussorgsky's Boris Godunov (1871) and Khovanshchina (1881), Tchaikovsky's Eugene Onegin (1878) and The Queen of Spades (1890), and Shostakovich's Fourth Symphony (1934). Offering new interpretations to enhance our understanding and appreciation of these important works, Gasparov also demonstrates how Russian music and cultural history illuminate one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusic and literature. 0aMusiczRussiaxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 0aOperazRussia. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300133165.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles